Promise me, Red,

1515
01:46:49,287 --> 01:46:51,288
if you ever get out,

1516
01:46:51,373 --> 01:46:53,415
find that spot.

1517
01:46:54,459 --> 01:46:57,190
At the base of that
wall, you'll find a rock that

1518
01:46:57,191 --> 01:46:59,922
has no earthly business in a Maine hayfield.

1519
01:47:00,006 --> 01:47:02,508
A piece of black, volcanic glass.

1520
01:47:05,678 --> 01:47:08,472
There's something buried under it
I want you to have.

1521
01:47:08,556 --> 01:47:10,557
What, Andy?

1522
01:47:10,642 --> 01:47:12,726
What's buried under there?

1523
01:47:14,522 --> 01:47:17,899
You'll have to pry it up to see.

1524
01:47:23,239 --> 01:47:25,323
No, I'm telling you, the guy is...

1525
01:47:26,367 --> 01:47:28,451
He's talking funnier.

1526
01:47:28,536 --> 01:47:31,913
- I'm really worried about him.
- We ought to keep an eye on him.

1527
01:47:31,997 --> 01:47:36,042
That's fine during the day,
but at night he's got that cell all to himself.

1528
01:47:37,128 --> 01:47:38,586
Oh, Lord.

1529
01:47:38,671 --> 01:47:40,713
What?

1530
01:47:42,383 --> 01:47:44,717
Andy come down to the loading dock today.

1531
01:47:44,802 --> 01:47:48,304
- He asked me for a length of rope.
- Rope?

1532
01:47:48,389 --> 01:47:50,223
Six feet long.

1533
01:47:50,307 --> 01:47:51,766
And you gave it to him?

1534
01:47:51,851 --> 01:47:54,519
Sure I did. Why wouldn't I?

1535
01:47:54,520 --> 01:47:56,229
Jesus, Heywood.

1536
01:47:56,313 --> 01:47:58,565
Hey, how the hell was I supposed to know?

1537
01:47:58,649 --> 01:48:00,567
Remember Brooks Hatlen?

1538
01:48:00,651 --> 01:48:01,693
No.

1539
01:48:02,736 --> 01:48:04,946
Andy would never do that.

1540
01:48:04,947 --> 01:48:07,031
Never.

1541
01:48:08,075 --> 01:48:10,160
I don't know.

1542
01:48:12,205 --> 01:48:14,290
Every man has his breaking point.

1543
01:48:16,918 --> 01:48:18,169
Lickety-split.

1544
01:48:18,253 --> 01:48:21,130
- I want to get home.
- Just about finished, sir.

1545
01:48:37,230 --> 01:48:39,315
Three deposits tonight.

1546
01:48:47,699 --> 01:48:49,783
Get my stuff down to the laundry.

1547
01:48:49,784 --> 01:48:53,245
And shine my shoes.
I want 'em looking like mirrors.

1548
01:48:53,330 --> 01:48:54,705
Yes, sir.

1549
01:49:00,003 --> 01:49:01,670
It's good having you back, Andy.

1550
01:49:01,755 --> 01:49:04,507
The place wasn't the same without you.

1551
01:49:51,556 --> 01:49:54,307
Lights out!

1552
01:50:25,048 --> 01:50:27,341
I've had some long nights in stir.

1553
01:50:28,385 --> 01:50:31,095
Alone in the dark with
nothing but your thoughts,

1554
01:50:31,179 --> 01:50:33,014
time can draw out like a blade.

1555
01:50:39,396 --> 01:50:41,731
That was the longest night of my life.

1556
01:50:57,873 --> 01:50:59,498
Give me a count.

1557
01:51:03,837 --> 01:51:05,880
Tier 3 South. Clear.

1558
01:51:05,964 --> 01:51:07,299
Tier 4 North. Clear.

1559
01:51:07,383 --> 01:51:10,969
- Tier 3 North. Clear.
- Man missing on Tier 2.

1560
01:51:11,054 --> 01:51:14,139
- Cell 245.
- Dufresne.

1561
01:51:14,223 --> 01:51:17,142
Get your ass out here, boy.
You're holding up the show.

1562
01:51:19,646 --> 01:51:23,690
Don't make me come down there.
I'll thump your skull for you.

1563
01:51:31,282 --> 01:51:34,660
Damn it, Dufresne, you're putting me behind!
I got a schedule to keep.

1564
01:51:34,744 --> 01:51:37,829
You'd better be sick or dead in there,
I shit you not!

1565
01:51:37,914 --> 01:51:39,748
You hear me?

1566
01:51:46,255 --> 01:51:48,340
Oh, my holy God.

1567
01:52:05,192 --> 01:52:07,902
I want every man on this cell block questioned.

1568
01:52:07,903 --> 01:52:10,113
- Start with that friend of his.
- Who?

1569
01:52:10,197 --> 01:52:11,406
Him!

1570
01:52:13,325 --> 01:52:15,410
Open 237.

1571
01:52:18,414 --> 01:52:20,540
What do you mean, he just wasn't here?

1572
01:52:20,624 --> 01:52:22,166
Don't say that to me, Haig.

1573
01:52:22,251 --> 01:52:24,502
Don't say that to me again.

1574
01:52:24,586 --> 01:52:25,670
But, sir, he wasn't.

1575
01:52:25,754 --> 01:52:27,922
I can see that, Haig!

1576
01:52:28,006 --> 01:52:29,799
You think I'm blind?

1577
01:52:29,800 --> 01:52:32,927
Is that what you're saying? Am I blind, Haig?

1578
01:52:33,011 --> 01:52:34,011
No, sir.

1579
01:52:34,096 --> 01:52:36,139
What about you?

1580
01:52:36,223 --> 01:52:38,057
Are you blind?

1581
01:52:38,142 --> 01:52:40,685
- Tell me what this is.
- Last night's count.

1582
01:52:40,769 --> 01:52:44,063
You see Dufresne's name there?
I sure do. See? Right there.

1583
01:52:44,148 --> 01:52:46,023
Dufresne.

1584
01:52:47,276 --> 01:52:48,943
He was in his cell at lights out.

1585
01:52:49,027 --> 01:52:52,238
It stands to reason
he'd still be here in the morning.

1586
01:52:53,323 --> 01:52:55,199
I want him found.

1587
01:52:55,284 --> 01:52:57,869
Not tomorrow, not after breakfast.

1588
01:52:57,953 --> 01:52:58,995
Now!

1589
01:52:58,996 --> 01:53:00,496
Yes, sir!

1590
01:53:01,623 --> 01:53:04,209
Let's go, let's go!
Move your butts! Move it!

1591
01:53:07,046 --> 01:53:08,088
Stand.

1592
01:53:09,215 --> 01:53:10,466
Well?

1593
01:53:13,845 --> 01:53:14,970
Well, what?

1594
01:53:15,054 --> 01:53:18,515
I see you two all the time.
You're thick as thieves, you are.

1595
01:53:19,559 --> 01:53:21,185
He must have said something.

1596
01:53:21,269 --> 01:53:23,312
No, sir, Warden.

1597
01:53:23,396 --> 01:53:24,855
Not a word.

1598
01:53:26,858 --> 01:53:28,859
Lord, it's a miracle!

1599
01:53:29,903 --> 01:53:32,362
A man up and vanished like a fart in the wind.

1600
01:53:32,447 --> 01:53:34,198
Nothing left but...

1601
01:53:34,282 --> 01:53:37,201
some damn rocks on a windowsill.

1602
01:53:37,285 --> 01:53:39,036
And that cupcake on the wall.

1603
01:53:39,120 --> 01:53:40,746
Let's ask her.

1604
01:53:40,830 --> 01:53:44,792
Maybe she knows. What say there,
Fuzzy Britches? Feel like talking?

1605
01:53:45,877 --> 01:53:46,960
Ah...

1606
01:53:46,961 --> 01:53:48,420
I guess not.

1607
01:53:48,505 --> 01:53:51,381
Why should she be any different?

1608
01:53:51,466 --> 01:53:53,926
This is a conspiracy.

1609
01:53:54,010 --> 01:53:56,220
That's what this is.

1610
01:53:56,304 --> 01:53:57,846
One big...

1611
01:53:57,931 --> 01:54:00,683
damn conspiracy!

1612
01:54:00,768 --> 01:54:03,436
And everyone's in on it!

1613
01:54:03,521 --> 01:54:04,813
Including her!

1614
01:54:39,473 --> 01:54:41,349
In 1966,

1615
01:54:41,433 --> 01:54:44,102
Andy Dufresne escaped

1616
01:54:44,186 --> 01:54:46,271
from Shawshank Prison.

1617
01:54:47,940 --> 01:54:50,692
All they found of him
was a muddy set of prison clothes,

1618
01:54:50,776 --> 01:54:52,819
a bar of soap

1619
01:54:52,903 --> 01:54:57,282
and an old rock hammer
damn near worn down to the nub.

1620
01:55:01,663 --> 01:55:06,500
I remember thinking it would take a man
600 years to tunnel through the wall with it.

1621
01:55:06,585 --> 01:55:09,295
Old Andy did it in less than 20.

1622
01:55:27,856 --> 01:55:29,940
Oh, Andy loved geology.

1623
01:55:30,984 --> 01:55:34,486
I imagine it appealed to his meticulous nature.

1624
01:55:34,571 --> 01:55:36,864
An Ice Age here,

1625
01:55:36,948 --> 01:55:39,533
a million years of mountain-building there.

1626
01:55:40,577 --> 01:55:42,995
Geology is the study of pressure and time.

1627
01:55:44,205 --> 01:55:46,248
That's all it takes, really.

1628
01:55:46,333 --> 01:55:48,375
Pressure...

1629
01:55:48,460 --> 01:55:50,336
and time.

1630
01:55:50,420 --> 01:55:53,756
That and a big goddamn poster.

1631
01:55:56,969 --> 01:55:58,345
Like I said,

1632
01:55:58,346 --> 01:56:02,140
in prison, a man will do most anything
to keep his mind occupied.

1633
01:56:04,936 --> 01:56:10,106
It turns out Andy's favorite hobby
was toting his wall out into the exercise yard.

1634
01:56:10,191 --> 01:56:12,275
A handful at a time.

1635
01:56:14,111 --> 01:56:16,279
I guess after Tommy was killed,

1636
01:56:16,364 --> 01:56:19,199
Andy decided he'd been here
just about long enough.

1637
01:56:19,283 --> 01:56:21,493
Lickety-split. I want to get home.

1638
01:56:22,787 --> 01:56:24,871
I'm just about finished, sir.

1639
01:56:46,268 --> 01:56:48,353
Three deposits tonight.

1640
01:56:55,529 --> 01:56:57,571
Andy did like he was told.

1641
01:56:58,615 --> 01:57:02,118
Buffed those shoes to a high mirror shine.

1642
01:57:05,706 --> 01:57:07,748
The guard simply didn't notice.

1643
01:57:07,833 --> 01:57:09,875
Neither did I.

1644
01:57:09,960 --> 01:57:14,296
I mean, seriously, how often
do you really look at a man's shoes?

1645
01:59:18,340 --> 01:59:24,512
Andy crawled to freedom through 500 yards
of shit-smelling foulness I can't even imagine.

1646
01:59:25,848 --> 01:59:27,849
Or maybe I just don't want to.

1647
01:59:32,563 --> 01:59:34,772
500 yards.

1648
01:59:35,816 --> 01:59:38,317
That's the length of five football fields.

1649
01:59:39,361 --> 01:59:41,612
Just shy of half a mile.

1650
02:00:36,836 --> 02:00:41,381
The next morning, right about the time
Raquel was spilling her little secret,

1651
02:00:41,466 --> 02:00:44,885
a man nobody ever laid eyes on before

1652
02:00:44,969 --> 02:00:47,388
strode into the Maine National Bank.

1653
02:00:47,473 --> 02:00:49,515
Until that moment,

1654
02:00:49,600 --> 02:00:51,476
he didn't exist,

1655
02:00:51,560 --> 02:00:52,894
except on paper.

1656
02:00:52,978 --> 02:00:54,020
May I help you?

1657
02:00:54,104 --> 02:00:56,147
He had all the proper ID,

1658
02:00:56,232 --> 02:00:59,859
driver's license, birth certificate,
social security card.

1659
02:00:59,944 --> 02:01:03,238
And the signature was a spot-on match.

1660
02:01:03,322 --> 02:01:06,366
I must say, I'm sorry
to be losing your business.

1661
02:01:06,450 --> 02:01:08,451
I hope you'll enjoy living abroad.

1662
02:01:08,535 --> 02:01:10,328
Thank you.

1663
02:01:10,412 --> 02:01:12,205
I'm sure I will.

1664
02:01:12,289 --> 02:01:14,415
Here's your cashier's check, sir.

1665
02:01:14,500 --> 02:01:16,542
Will there be anything else?

1666
02:01:16,627 --> 02:01:17,627
Please...

1667
02:01:17,711 --> 02:01:20,797
Would you add this to your outgoing mail?

1668
02:01:20,881 --> 02:01:23,091
I'd be happy to.

1669
02:01:23,175 --> 02:01:25,510
- Good day, sir.
- Good day.

1670
02:01:25,594 --> 02:01:30,390
Mr. Stevens visited nearly a dozen banks
in the Portland area that morning.

1671
02:01:31,558 --> 02:01:38,022
All told, he blew town with better than $370,000
of Warden Norton's money.

1672
02:01:38,107 --> 02:01:40,566
Severance pay for 19 years.

1673
02:01:48,702 --> 02:01:50,995
Good morning, Portland Daily Bugle.

1674
02:02:43,716 --> 02:02:46,718
Byron Hadley?
You have the right to remain silent.

1675
02:02:46,802 --> 02:02:49,116
If you give up the right
to remain silent, anything

1676
02:02:49,117 --> 02:02:51,431
you say will be held against you in court.

1677
02:02:51,515 --> 02:02:53,391
I wasn't there to see it.

1678
02:02:53,476 --> 02:02:58,355
But I hear Byron Hadley started sobbing
like a little girl when they took him away.

1679
02:03:03,778 --> 02:03:06,571
Norton had no intention of going that quietly.

1680
02:03:22,546 --> 02:03:24,005
Samuel Norton?

1681
02:03:24,090 --> 02:03:27,342
We have a warrant for your arrest. Open up.

1682
02:03:30,221 --> 02:03:31,346
Norton!

1683
02:03:31,430 --> 02:03:33,098
Open the door.

1684
02:03:33,182 --> 02:03:34,933
I'm not sure which key it is.

1685
02:03:37,812 --> 02:03:39,479
Norton!

1686
02:03:44,945 --> 02:03:47,029
Make it easy on yourself, Norton.

1687
02:03:58,333 --> 02:04:01,919
I like to think
the last thing that went through his head,

1688
02:04:02,003 --> 02:04:03,712
other than that bullet,

1689
02:04:03,797 --> 02:04:07,800
was to wonder how the hell
Andy Dufresne ever got the best of him.

1690
02:04:09,469 --> 02:04:10,553
Carter, James...

1691
02:04:10,637 --> 02:04:14,014
Not long after the Warden
deprived us of his company,

1692
02:04:14,099 --> 02:04:16,350
I got a postcard in the mail.

1693
02:04:18,061 --> 02:04:20,479
It was blank but the postmark said...

1694
02:04:20,564 --> 02:04:23,315
Fort Hancock, Texas.

1695
02:04:23,400 --> 02:04:25,443
Fort Hancock.

1696
02:04:25,527 --> 02:04:27,570
Right on the border.

1697
02:04:27,654 --> 02:04:29,697
That's where Andy crossed.

1698
02:04:29,781 --> 02:04:33,659
When I picture him heading south
in his own car with the top down,

1699
02:04:34,703 --> 02:04:36,787
it always makes me laugh.

1700
02:04:38,206 --> 02:04:40,250
Andy Dufresne,

1701
02:04:40,334 --> 02:04:42,711
who crawled through a river of shit

1702
02:04:42,795 --> 02:04:44,880
and came out clean on the other side.

1703
02:04:46,090 --> 02:04:48,133
Andy Dufresne,

1704
02:04:48,217 --> 02:04:50,135
headed for the Pacific.

1705
02:04:52,722 --> 02:04:54,764
Hadley's got him by the toes, right?

1706
02:04:54,849 --> 02:04:59,060
And he says, "I believe this boy's
about to have himself an accident."

1707
02:04:59,145 --> 02:05:02,314
Those of us who knew him best
talk about him often.

1708
02:05:02,398 --> 02:05:04,649
I swear, the stuff he pulled...

1709
02:05:04,734 --> 02:05:07,235
"These friends of mine
could use a couple of beers!"

1710
02:05:07,320 --> 02:05:09,404
- And he got it.
- And he got it!

1711
02:05:10,573 --> 02:05:12,949
Sometimes it makes me sad, though,

1712
02:05:13,034 --> 02:05:15,076
Andy being gone.

1713
02:05:15,161 --> 02:05:19,164
I have to remind myself
that some birds aren't meant to be caged.

1714
02:05:20,249 --> 02:05:22,334
Their feathers are just too bright.

1715
02:05:23,878 --> 02:05:25,921
And when they fly away,

1716
02:05:26,005 --> 02:05:29,925
the part of you that knows
it was a sin to lock them up does rejoice.

1717
02:05:31,677 --> 02:05:33,136
But still...

1718
02:05:33,221 --> 02:05:37,391
the place you live in is that much more drab
and empty that they're gone.

1719
02:05:41,939 --> 02:05:44,190
I guess I just miss my friend.

1720
02:06:08,173 --> 02:06:10,049
Please sit down.

1721
02:06:15,639 --> 02:06:17,765
Ellis Boyd Redding.

1722
02:06:17,849 --> 02:06:21,227
Your files say you've served
40 years of a life sentence.

1723
02:06:21,311 --> 02:06:23,688
Do you feel you've been rehabilitated?

1724
02:06:25,816 --> 02:06:27,900
Rehabilitated?

1725
02:06:29,444 --> 02:06:31,529
Well, now, let me see.

1726
02:06:32,573 --> 02:06:34,907
You know, I don't have any idea
what that means.

1727
02:06:36,703 --> 02:06:39,246
Well, it means you're ready to rejoin society...

1728
02:06:39,330 --> 02:06:41,873
I know what you think it means, sonny.

1729
02:06:44,252 --> 02:06:46,336
To me, it's just a made-up word.

1730
02:06:47,380 --> 02:06:49,631
A politician's word so that...

1731
02:06:49,716 --> 02:06:55,220
young fellas like yourself
can wear a suit and a tie and have a job.

1732
02:06:57,640 --> 02:06:59,725
What do you really want to know?

1733
02:07:00,893 --> 02:07:02,811
Am I sorry for what I did?

1734
02:07:02,895 --> 02:07:04,605
Well, are you?

1735
02:07:06,232 --> 02:07:08,817
There's not a day goes by I don't feel regret.

1736
02:07:10,403 --> 02:07:13,530
Not because I'm in here
or because you think I should.

1737
02:07:17,327 --> 02:07:19,411
I look back on the way I was then.

1738
02:07:21,998 --> 02:07:24,041
A young...

1739
02:07:24,125 --> 02:07:27,210
stupid kid who committed that terrible crime.

1740
02:07:31,049 --> 02:07:33,133
I wanna talk to him.

1741
02:07:34,511 --> 02:07:36,679
I wanna try and talk some sense to him,

1742
02:07:37,723 --> 02:07:39,807
tell him the way things are.

1743
02:07:41,977 --> 02:07:44,062
But I can't.

1744
02:07:45,272 --> 02:07:47,357
That kid's long gone.

1745
02:07:48,651 --> 02:07:50,735
This old man is all that's left.

1746
02:07:52,863 --> 02:07:54,364
I gotta live with that.

1747
02:07:55,699 --> 02:07:57,492
Rehabilitated?

1748
02:07:57,576 --> 02:07:59,577
It's just a bullshit word.

1749
02:07:59,662 --> 02:08:05,583
So you go on and stamp your form, sonny,
and stop wasting my time.

1750
02:08:06,669 --> 02:08:08,711
Because to tell you the truth,

1751
02:08:08,796 --> 02:08:11,297
I don't give a shit.

1752
02:09:37,511 --> 02:09:39,596
Here you go, miss.

1753
02:09:41,599 --> 02:09:43,057
Rest room break, boss?

1754
02:09:49,106 --> 02:09:53,401
You don't need to ask me every time you need
to go take a piss. Just go. Understand?

1755
02:09:54,612 --> 02:09:56,279
Yes, sir.

1756
02:10:06,332 --> 02:10:09,375
40 years
I've been asking permission to piss.

1757
02:10:10,377 --> 02:10:12,587
I can't squeeze a drop without say-so.

1758
02:10:16,717 --> 02:10:18,802
There's a harsh truth to face.

1759
02:10:20,763 --> 02:10:23,097
No way I'm gonna make it on the outside.

1760
02:10:31,316 --> 02:10:34,777
All I do any more
is think of ways to break my parole...

1761
02:10:35,821 --> 02:10:37,905
..so maybe they'd send me back.

1762
02:10:43,411 --> 02:10:45,496
A terrible thing to live in fear.

1763
02:10:46,873 --> 02:10:50,251
Brooks Hatlen knew it, knew it all too well.

1764
02:10:52,420 --> 02:10:55,214
All I want is to be back
where things make sense,

1765
02:10:56,258 --> 02:10:58,759
where I won't have to be afraid all the time.

1766
02:11:01,638 --> 02:11:03,722
Only one thing stops me.

1767
02:11:04,766 --> 02:11:06,851
A promise I made to Andy.

1768
02:11:27,582 --> 02:11:29,666
Here it is.

1769
02:11:39,468 --> 02:11:41,553
Much obliged, sir.

1770
02:15:20,360 --> 02:15:21,652
Dear Red,

1771
02:15:21,736 --> 02:15:24,196
if you're reading this, you've gotten out.

1772
02:15:24,280 --> 02:15:28,534
And if you've come this far,
maybe you're willing to come a little further.

1773
02:15:28,618 --> 02:15:31,203
You remember the name of the town, don't you?

1774
02:15:33,498 --> 02:15:35,582
Zihuatanejo.

1775
02:15:36,626 --> 02:15:37,835
I could use a good man

1776
02:15:37,919 --> 02:15:39,962
to help me get my project on wheels.

1777
02:15:40,046 --> 02:15:42,172
I'll keep an eye out for you

1778
02:15:42,257 --> 02:15:44,299
and the chessboard ready.

1779
02:15:45,343 --> 02:15:46,718
Remember, Red,

1780
02:15:46,803 --> 02:15:48,846
hope is a good thing.

1781
02:15:48,930 --> 02:15:50,973
Maybe the best of things.

1782
02:15:51,057 --> 02:15:53,142
And no good thing ever dies.

1783
02:15:54,185 --> 02:15:56,645
I will be hoping that this letter finds you

1784
02:15:56,729 --> 02:15:58,772
and finds you well.

1785
02:15:58,857 --> 02:16:01,358
Your friend, Andy.

1786
02:16:35,936 --> 02:16:39,814
Get busy living or get busy dying.

1787
02:16:42,318 --> 02:16:44,402
That's goddamn right.

1788
02:16:49,909 --> 02:16:52,035
For the second time in my life,

1789
02:16:52,119 --> 02:16:54,204
I'm guilty of committing a crime.

1790
02:16:55,873 --> 02:16:57,957
Parole violation.

1791
02:16:57,958 --> 02:17:01,669
Of course, I doubt they'll toss up
any roadblocks for that.

1792
02:17:02,922 --> 02:17:04,964
Not for an old crook like me.

1793
02:17:05,049 --> 02:17:07,133
Fort Hancock, Texas, please.

1794
02:17:10,846 --> 02:17:14,975
I find I'm so excited I can barely sit still
or hold a thought in my head.

1795
02:17:16,019 --> 02:17:19,021
I think it's the excitement
only a free man can feel.

1796
02:17:19,105 --> 02:17:21,815
A free man at the start of a long journey

1797
02:17:21,900 --> 02:17:24,818
whose conclusion is uncertain.

1798
02:17:27,697 --> 02:17:29,865
I hope I can make it across the border.

1799
02:17:31,743 --> 02:17:34,536
I hope to see my friend and shake his hand.

1800
02:17:36,915 --> 02:17:40,125
I hope the Pacific is as blue
as it has been in my dreams.

1801
02:17:42,879 --> 02:17:44,755
I hope.